nigd Koninkrijk","{Lln ap Gwrgan}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië","Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1350–":"about 1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1379–Female":"1379–Deceased","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"about 1400","1365":"1365","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1350":"about 1350","Llangyndeym, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Lln ap Gwrgan}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dwnn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinn</b>, <b>Ó Doinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘brown-haired’ or ‘chieftain’. Compare   Dunne  . This name has sometimes been Anglicized as   Brown  .","English: nickname for a dark complexioned or swarthy man, from Middle English <i>dun</i> ‘dun, dark’ (Old English <i>dunn</i> ‘dull brown’).","Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’. Compare   Dun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Cahal, Eamonn, Grainne.","Chinese: variant of   Dunn  .","German (<b>Dünne</b>): nickname for a slender, skinny person, from Middle High German <i>dünne</i> ‘thin’."]},{"name":"Brown","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: generally a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion, Middle English <i>br(o)un</i>, from Old English <i>brūn</i> or Old French <i>brun</i>. This word is occasionally found in Old French, Middle English and Old Norse as a personal name or byname (Middle English personal name <i>Brun</i>, <i>Broun</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Bruno</i>, Old English <i>Brūn</i>, or possibly Old Norse <i>Brúnn</i> or <i>Brúni</i>). <i>Brun-</i> was also an ancient Germanic name-forming element. Some instances of Old English <i>Brūn</i> as a personal name may therefore be short forms of compound names such as <i>Brūngar</i>, <i>Brūnwine</i>, etc. As a Scottish and Irish name, it sometimes represents a translation of Gaelic <i>Donn</i> (see below). <i>Brown</i> (including in the senses below) is the fourth most frequent surname in the US. It is also very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below).","Irish and Scottish: adopted for <b>Ó Duinn</b> (see   Dunn  ) or for any of the many Irish and Scottish Gaelic names containing the element <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ (also meaning ‘chieftain’), for example   Donahue  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."]},{"name":"Don","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Agustin, Jose, Miguel, Pablo, Ramon, Ruben, Adriana, Ausencio, Eduardo, Enrique, Erasmo, Francisco.","English and Scottish: variant of   Dunn  .","English and Scottish: variant of   Dun  , a habitational name from Dun in Angus, Scotland."]},{"name":"Done","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alfredo, Angel, Berto, Cristobal, Dinora, Eloisa, Francisco, Generoso, Gustavo, Juan.","English: variant of <b>Donne</b>, itself a variant of   Dunn  ."]},{"name":"Dunsford","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dunsford in Devon, from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Dunn</i> (see   Dunn  ) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. Although Dunsforth in Yorkshire also gave rise to the surname, it appears not to have survived the medieval period."]},{"name":"Dunford","meanings":["habitational name from Dunford Bridge, in Thurlstone (Yorkshire), so called from the river <i>Don</i> (a British name possibly meaning ‘river’) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, or from Dunford House in Methley (Yorkshire), named in Old English as ‘Dunn's ford’ (see   Dunn   2).","variant of <b>Durnford</b>, a habitational name from Durnford in Wiltshire, arising from Old English <i>dierne</i> + <i>ford</i> ‘hidden ford’. Alternatively, the name may perhaps arise from Dunford, alias Durnford, in Addlestone (Surrey).","English:"]},{"name":"Donn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Chaim, Isaak, Meyer, Zorach.","English (Lancashire) and Scottish (Caithness): variant of   Dunn  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Don  ."]},{"name":"Dunson","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a patronymic from   Dunn   2 or4. Compare   Donson  ."]},{"name":"Dun","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus.","English: variant of   Dunn  .","Dutch: nickname from Middle Dutch <i>dun</i> ‘thin’."]}]},{"name":"Gwladys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old form of   Gladys  , of uncertain derivation."],"variants":[]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwladys verch Henry Dwnn was born about 1350, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, her father, Henry ap Griffith Dwnn, was 21 and her mother, Annes ferch Ieuan Lloyd, was 21. She had at least 2 sons with Gwilym Ap Philip."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1369–Male":"1369–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"umbes 1400","1365":"1365","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Llangyndeym, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","{Lln ap Gwrgan}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1350–":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1379–Female":"1379–Kuollut","1369–Male":"1369–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1330–1411":"1330–1411","1330–Female":"1330–Kuollut","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"noin 1400","1365":"1365","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","about 1350":"noin 1350","Llangyndeym, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carmarthenshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","{Lln ap Gwrgan}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italia","Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llanfoist, Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Carm